{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470315"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:36:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:36:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.01,0.24,0.33,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107500"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89980"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"5869"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"},{"type":"tags","id":"13230"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15597"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39428"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107500"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 11-year-old female is brought into the emergency department by her parents. Collateral history from her parents reports an episode of unusual lip smacking followed by motionless staring into space and becoming unresponsive when spoken to. This is followed by sudden stiffness and then uncontrollable movements. This episode lasted approximately 30 seconds to one minute and is associated with lethargy and confusion afterwards. Prior to this, the patient reports hearing voices and strong feelings of having experienced certain situations to her parents. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ethosuximide","Gabapentin","Levetiracetam","Carbamazepine","Lamotrigine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child is experiencing focal seizures with impaired awareness (previously termed complex partial seizures) most consistent with temporal lobe epilepsy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA focal seizure, also known as a partial seizure, is a seizure that originates in one specific area of the brain, rather than the entire brain. These seizures can manifest in various ways depending on the brain area involved, including changes in awareness, sensation, movement, or emotions\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPreceding events involved in temporal lobe epilepsy can present with dyscognitive aura presenting as auditory hallucinations and d\u00e9j\u00e0 vu. Additionally, automatism such as lip smacking, chewing or swallowing are also common presentations associated with 40-80% of temporal lob epilepsy. In children, it is common to observe behavioural arrest and unresponsiveness in focal seizures of temporal onset. Furthermore, focal seizures can evolve into bilateral (secondarily generalised) tonic-clonic seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarbamazepine\u003C/strong\u003E is generally considered the first-line treatment for focal (partial) seizures in Australia, supported by high-quality evidence, and is thus the correct answer. Typically, patients are commenced on a low dose and slowly up-titrated to an appropriate dose. For example, children are prescribed 2.5mg/kg orally to 5mg/kg twice daily, then up-titrated to 10mg/kg twice daily. In adults, a low dose (100 mg nocte) is started and then increased on a weekly basis to 200 mg bd. This dose may have to be reduced if side effects (diplopia) occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevetiracetam\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Elamotrigine and gabapentin\u003C/strong\u003E are second-line pharmacological agents and are therefore the incorrect answer. For patients presenting with tonic-clonic seizures where generalised or focal (partial) onset seizure is unclear, \u2018broad-spectrum\u2019 antiepileptic drugs for both types of seizures such as levetiracetam, lamotrigine and sodium valproate should be considered. Levetiracetam is considered the first-line therapy in females of childbearing age who do not have reliable contraception. In children, adult males, and females with reliable contraception, sodium valproate is considered the first line. However, based on the history provided, it is likely that the tonic-clonic seizure is caused by a focal (partial) onset, and therefore carbamazepine is the most appropriate answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEthosuximide \u003C/strong\u003Eis the first-line agent used in absence seizures and is an incorrect answer. This patient presents with focal seizures with impaired awareness, which can be differentiated from absence seizure, due to the presence of post-ictal confusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbamazepine is a recommended first-line choice for focal seizure."],"references":["Nevitt SJ, Sudell M, Weston J, Tudur Smith C, Marson AG. Antiepileptic drug monotherapy for epilepsy: a network meta-analysis of individual participant data.\u00a0Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2017;12(12):CD011412. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35363878/","Stevens CE, Stafstrom CE. Pharmacotherapy for Focal Seizures in Children and Adolescents. Drugs 2018; 78:1321-37. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30128698/","Kumar A, Ighodaro ET, Sharma S. Focal Impaired Awareness Seizure. [Updated 2024 Mar 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519030/","Epilepsy and seizures. In Electronic therapeutic guidelines complete [online]. Retrieved September 16, 2024. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89980"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89980"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-30T14:53:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T14:54:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107500"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1